\pard\plain \ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Let\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s take a closer look at \u8220\'93Scrivenings\u8221\'94 mode. The whole point of Scrivener is to make working on a long text easier by allowing you to break it up into smaller pieces, but you will often want to see how those smaller pieces fit into the greater whole. This is what Scrivenings mode lets you do.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1040\fi562\sa120\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 There are two ways of entering Scrivenings mode:}
\par\pard\plain \li850\fi561\ql\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs26\b0\i0	1.	}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0 You can select a folder or container in the binder that contains text subdocuments, and use Scrivenings mode to view all of the documents inside the folder (including the folder itself, if it has text associated with it) as though they were one long document.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs26\b0\i0	2.	}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0 You can select arbitrary documents in the binder and view them as though they were a single document.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1040\fi562\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 We already did (1) in Step 7, so let\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s try viewing arbitrary documents this time. Once you\u8217\'92ve finished reading this paragraph, click on \u8220\'93START HERE\u8221\'94 at the top of the binder and then, holding down the }{\f2\fs26\b1\i0 Ctrl}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0  key, click on \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Step 7: Changing Editor Views\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93Step 11: Scrivenings\u8221\'94, so that all three documents get selected. Once that\u8217\'92s done, ensure that the stack of papers is selected in the \u8220\'93Group Mode\u8221\'94 control in the toolbar, and then scroll down towards the bottom of the text that gets loaded into this editor and look for the pink highlighting below\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 do that now.}
